description:
lib.rs:135-145:
```rust
let (mount, secret_path) = match parsed.path().find('/') {
    Some(i) => (
        parsed.path()[..i].to_string(),
        parsed.path()[i + 1..].to_string(),
    ),
    None => return Err(SecretError::InvalidUri("vault URI must be secretx:vault:<mount>/<path>".into())),
};
```

Idiomatic:
```rust
let (mount, secret_path) = parsed.path().split_once('/').ok_or_else(|| {
    SecretError::InvalidUri("vault URI must be secretx:vault:<mount>/<path>".into())
})?;
let mount = mount.to_string();
let secret_path = secret_path.to_string();
```

split_once is the canonical way to split-on-first-occurrence; the find-then-slice pattern is a pre-1.52 idiom that survived. clippy::manual_split_once would lint this in some configurations.

P2 idiom finding (clippy-tier).
